# Evaluation

**Evaluation** is the systematic process of assessing the performance, quality, or behavior of an entity — such as a large language model (LLM), an agent, a prompt, or a system component — against a defined set of criteria or ground truth. In the context of this Personal LLM Wiki, evaluation is a critical feedback mechanism that transforms raw outputs into actionable insights. Its main significance lies in enabling iterative improvement: by quantifying how well a component performs (e.g., accuracy, relevance, safety, or speed), users can identify failures, tune prompts, adjust parameters, or retrain models. Evaluation is tightly coupled with actions like logging test results, setting benchmarks, and maintaining evaluation datasets; it also promotes associations with entities such as “Metrics,” “Test Suites,” and “Monitoring.” Without rigorous evaluation, an LLM system risks blind operation, amplifying errors or biases without a mechanism for correction.</data>
